Using the equation in Step 11, the price of the put option is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{P}&=\$65,000\times2.71828^{-(0.07)(5)}+\$25,233-\$62,000\\[15pt]
&=\$65,000\times0.7047+\$25,233-\$62,000\\[15pt]
&=\$45,806+\$25,233-\$62,000\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$9,039}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the value of the put option is $9,039.

The gain or loss on equity is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Change in Equity}&=\$12,856-\$9,039\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$3,817}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the gain for stockholders is $3,817.

The gain or loss on debt is solved as follows: 

&nbsp;

$$\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Change in Debt}&=\$16,194-\$16,194\\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\$0}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, there's no gain or loss for bondholders.
